        <div class="section-header">
            <h2>I. The Geological & Legal Distinction</h2>
        </div>

        <p>The 1935 Globe Equity Decree governs the alluvial subflow of the Gila River. Project 88 identifies and accesses a separate system: the **Granite-Vault Aquifer formations**. This system is defined by deep geological containment that has been isolated from the river's adjudicated flows since before the Decree was enacted.</p>
        
        <div class="tech-callout">
            <div class="tech-text">
                <h3>Proven Since the 1890s</h3>
                <p>This is not 'new' water. It is a historically proven, re-accessed resource. Mining operations and USGS geological surveys from the late 19th and early 20th centuries documented deep bedrock aquifers capable of sustainable flow, geologically distinct from the sandy river plain. We are leveraging this archived data to build a new model of containment.</p>
            </div>
            <img src="assets/granite_aquifer.png" alt="A cross-section diagram showing the shallow Gila River Alluvium separated by a fault boundary from the deeper, non-adjudicated Granite-Vault Aquifer system where Project 88 target water is located." class="tech-image" />
        </div>

        <div class="section-header">
            <h2>II. Proven Technology: Managed Aquifer Recharge (MAR)</h2>
        </div>

        <p>Project 88 isn't an experimental pilot. It deploys proven Managed Aquifer Recharge technology—repressurizing deep geology during surplus flow events to create reliable, multi-generational groundwater storage.</p>
        <p>We leverage the same logic and engineering used successfully for decades by major regional precedents: **Salt River Project (GRUSP)** and the **City of Chandler** water management teams.</p>

        <div id="sources-partners">
            <h3>III. Verifiable Data & Verified Partners</h3>
            <p>Our hydrogeological mapping draws exclusively from publicly verifiable archives, combining 130 years of documentation with modern AI-driven geological modeling.</p>
